  <h3>NMN: NAD+ Restoration</h3>
  <p>Nicotinamide Mononucleotide converts directly to NAD+, a coenzyme that powers over 500 biological reactions. NAD+ levels decline roughly 50% between ages 40 and 60. This decline is now considered a hallmark of metabolic aging.</p>
  <p>NMN's three critical functions: powering sirtuins (the longevity-associated proteins that regulate gene expression), maintaining mitochondrial membrane potential for ATP production, and supporting PARP enzymes responsible for DNA repair. The direct conversion pathway bypasses rate-limiting steps that slow other NAD+ precursors like NR and niacin.</p>
</div>

<div class="cd cp">
