  <h3>Thymosin Alpha-1: Thymic Regeneration</h3>
  <p>The thymus shrinks by approximately 3% per year after puberty, progressively reducing naive T-cell production. By age 65, most adults have lost over 85% of thymic mass. <a href="/articles/thymosin-alpha-1-immune-guide">Thymosin Alpha-1</a> counteracts this involution through direct stimulation of thymic epithelial cells.</p>
  <p>The immune restoration follows a predictable timeline. Weeks 1 to 2 bring increased naive T-cell production. By month 1, inflammatory cytokines (IL-6, TNF-alpha) drop measurably. At month 3, pathogen response improves significantly. This phased recovery mirrors the natural thymic maturation process, just compressed into a much shorter window.</p>
